The usual response to this complaint in the Ruby/Rails community is that optimizing for nanoseconds, or even milliseconds doesn't matter when the same operation also involves multiple database queries or API calls.Let's take this example from the article:  Billing::Plan.find_or_create_all_by_attrs!(
    1.month => {standard: 10, pro: 50, enterprise: 100},
    1.year => {standard: 100, pro: 500, enterprise: 1000}
  )

This ensures six billing plans are created. That means 6 DB queries and 6 Stripe API queries, at a minimum.
